M|bloom-filter-caching|name: bloom-filter-caching
M|bloom-filter-caching|description: Bloom filter caching str for YVON. Covers membership testing (seen before? cached?), false positive rate tuning, cache stampede prevention, and YVON-specific use cases (deduplicating cp c
M|bloom-filter-caching|version: 1.0.0
M|bloom-filter-caching|A bloom filter is a probabilistic data structure that answers "has this item been seen before?" with zero false negatives and a tunable false positive rate. For YVON, this is the right tool when:
M|bloom-filter-caching|- You need to avoid re-fetching or re-processing cnt you've already seen
M|bloom-filter-caching|- You need a fast membership check before hitting Supabase (reduce DB queries)
M|bloom-filter-caching|- You need to pre-screen rate limit candidates before the full rate limit check
M|bloom-filter-caching|- You need to deduplicate cp URLs, post IDs, or cg assets before storing
M|bloom-filter-caching|**Key property:** A bloom filter never says "not seen" when it has been seen. It may say "seen" when it hasn't (false positive). Tune the false positive rate based on the cost of a false positive in y
M|bloom-filter-caching|A bloom filter uses multiple hash functions mapped to a bit array:
M|bloom-filter-caching|- **Add item:** Hash the item with k functions, set k bits to 1
M|bloom-filter-caching|- **Check item:** Hash the item, check if all k bits are 1 — if any is 0, definitely not seen; if all are 1, probably seen
M|bloom-filter-caching|**False positive rate formula:**
M|bloom-filter-caching|`p ≈ (1 - e^(-kn/m))^k`
M|bloom-filter-caching|- `n` = number of items inserted
M|bloom-filter-caching|- `m` = bit array size
M|bloom-filter-caching|- `k` = number of hash functions (optimal: `k = (m/n) ln 2 ≈ 0.693 m/n`)
M|bloom-filter-caching|**Rule of thumb for YVON:**
M|bloom-filter-caching|- Expected < 10K items, 1% false positive rate → 95KB filter
M|bloom-filter-caching|- Expected < 100K items, 0.1% false positive rate → 1.8MB filter
M|bloom-filter-caching|Before fetching a cp URL through Apify, check the bloom filter. False positive (skip a new URL) rate: acceptable at 1%. Saves Apify API credits on already-processed cnt.
M|bloom-filter-caching|Before inserting a post/cnt item into Supabase, check the bloom filter. Prevents duplicate rows from parallel ingestion jobs without a DB unique constraint check on every insert.
M|bloom-filter-caching|Before a full Supabase rate_limits table lookup, check the bloom filter: "has this IP made a request in this window?" False positive → proceed to full check (safe). Eliminates 80–90% of DB queries on 
M|bloom-filter-caching|Track which cnt items have already been scored/ranked this ses. Avoids re-running expensive anl computations on unchanged data.
M|bloom-filter-caching|```typescript
M|bloom-filter-caching|import { BloomFilter } from 'bloom-filters' // npm: bloom-filters
M|bloom-filter-caching|const filter = BloomFilter.create(10000, 0.01) // 10K items, 1% FP rate
M|bloom-filter-caching|// Add
M|bloom-filter-caching|filter.add(itemId)
M|bloom-filter-caching|// Check
M|bloom-filter-caching|if (filter.has(itemId)) {
M|bloom-filter-caching|// probably seen — verify against DB if false positive cost is high
M|bloom-filter-caching|} else {
M|bloom-filter-caching|// definitely not seen — skip DB check
M|bloom-filter-caching|}
M|bloom-filter-caching|```
M|bloom-filter-caching|Serialize the filter to a Buffer and store in Supabase storage or a `bloom_filters` table. Reload at route initialization. Flush back to storage after N additions.
M|bloom-filter-caching|```typescript
M|bloom-filter-caching|// Serialize
M|bloom-filter-caching|const serialized = Buffer.from(filter.saveAsJSON())
M|bloom-filter-caching|// Store in Supabase
M|bloom-filter-caching|await supabase.from('bloom_filters').upsert({
M|bloom-filter-caching|filter_key: 'competitor_urls',
M|bloom-filter-caching|venture_slug: ventureSlug,
M|bloom-filter-caching|data: serialized.toString('base64'),
M|bloom-filter-caching|updated_at: new Date().toISOString()
M|bloom-filter-caching|})
M|bloom-filter-caching|// Reload
M|bloom-filter-caching|const { data } = await supabase.from('bloom_filters')
M|bloom-filter-caching|.select('data')
M|bloom-filter-caching|.eq('filter_key', 'competitor_urls')
M|bloom-filter-caching|.eq('venture_slug', ventureSlug)
M|bloom-filter-caching|.single()
M|bloom-filter-caching|const filter = BloomFilter.fromJSON(JSON.parse(Buffer.from(data.data, 'base64').toString()))
M|bloom-filter-caching|```
M|bloom-filter-caching|Keep a short-lived bloom filter in Edge middleware mem for IP pre-screening. Resets on cold start (acceptable — just falls back to full DB check).
M|bloom-filter-caching|Before approving any bloom filter implementation:
M|bloom-filter-caching|- [ ] Is the false positive rate defined and acceptable for this use case?
M|bloom-filter-caching|- [ ] Is there a fallback when the filter says "seen" but the item is actually new? (DB verification for high-cost false positives)
M|bloom-filter-caching|- [ ] Is the filter size bounded? Will it stay within mem limits at maximum expected item count?
M|bloom-filter-caching|- [ ] For persistent filters: is there a reset/rotation schedule when the filter approaches saturation?
M|bloom-filter-caching|- [ ] Is venture_slug scoping applied so Novizio and Hourbour filters don't contaminate each other?
M|bloom-filter-caching|`bloom-filters` (npm) — pure TypeScript, no native deps, works on Vercel Edge.
M|bloom-filter-caching|`npm install bloom-filters`